    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Majority of checks are already covered by LuaLS and Stylua. Luacheck provides lots false-positive results we need to disable with comments.\n\nThe following are the remaining [checks Luacheck has](https://luacheck.readthedocs.io/en/stable/warnings.html).\n\n| Code | Description                                                         | Comment                                                                |\n|------|---------------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| 111  | Setting an undefined global variable.                               | LuaLS only checks global variables must be uppercase, so mostly equiv  |\n| 314  | Value of a field in a table literal is unused.                      | sounds useful                                                          |\n| 512  | Loop can be executed at most once.                                  | not that useful                                                        |\n| 541  | An empty do end block.                                              | probably a LuaLS bug since it checks empty loop/if statements          |\n| 561  | Cyclomatic complexity of a function is too high.                    | huh?                                                                   |\n| 581  | Negation of a relational operator- operator can be flipped.         | we disable                                                         |\n| 582  | Error prone negation: negation has a higher priority than equality. | sounds useful                                                          |",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "We ignore `581` since it's not true when tables are involved. (And, yes, `561` is a weird one. I don't think we even enable the ~chromatic~ cyclomatic check.)\n\nAssuming that `541` can get fixed (not a big loss in the meantime), this only leaves `582` and potentially `314`. The former sounds also prone to false positives, and the latter would be something that could be proposed to luals/emmyluals?",
